286-361. Description of the foot race. Aeneas chooses a meadow, encir- cled bywooded hills, as a circus or stadium. He invites all who wish to make trial of their speed in a foot race to present themselves. The most prominent competitors are Nisus, Euryalus, Diores, Salius, Patron, Helymus, and Panopes. Nisus takes the lead, Salius is next, and third Euryalus, fol· lowed by Helymus and Diores. Near the goal Nisus falls down, but gives the victory to his friend Euryalus by tripping up Salius. Helymus takes the sec- ond prize, and Diores the third. ·
